# 🚨 Cybercrime Case Study: UPI Payment Fraud in India

## 📌 Overview
UPI (Unified Payments Interface) fraud is a rapidly increasing cybercrime in India where attackers trick users into authorizing payments instead of receiving money.

## 🧠 How the Fraud Happens
A common scenario involves a student selling an item online (e.g., books or gadgets). The scammer contacts the student pretending to be a buyer and agrees to pay via UPI.

Instead of sending money, the scammer sends a **“Collect Request”** on apps like Google Pay or PhonePe. They instruct the student to “accept” the request to receive payment. Due to lack of awareness, the student enters their UPI PIN, unknowingly **authorizing a payment** to the scammer.

In some cases, fraudsters also send fake screenshots showing “payment successful” to gain trust. Others may pose as customer support agents and ask users to install screen-sharing apps, gaining access to banking details.

## 🎯 Target Victims
- College students  
- First-time digital payment users  
- People unfamiliar with UPI features  

## ⚠️ Consequences
- Immediate financial loss  
- Unauthorized transactions  
- Compromise of personal and banking data  

## 💡 Key Insight
UPI apps never require entering a PIN to **receive** money — only to **send** money. Lack of awareness of this basic rule is what makes users vulnerable to such scams.
